\f1\b Folder Structure
\f0\b0 \
package.json - contains dependencies and scripts required for the project\
package-lock.json - consistent installation of your dependencies\
node_modules - folder where all the dependencies are installed\
manifest.json - for progressive web app\
index.html is the only HTML file that you are going to have in your application. We will build SPA and this is it. View might change dynamically in the browser. Normally you are not going to change this file (specially body tag). 
\f1\b Here React is going to control UI and for that you have one div tag <div id="root"></div>
\f0\b0 \
Starting point for our Application is index.js. In index.js we specify root component which is App component and DOM element which will be controlled by React. The DOM element in our example is an element with an id of root (and this the element in our index.html file). We call this div element as the root DOM node because everything inside it will be controlled by React. For the hello world application the app component is rendered inside root DOM node.\
Now app component is in App.js file. App component represnts the view which we see in the browser.\
App.css - For CSS\
App.test.js - for unit test case\
//serviceWorker.js - for progressive web app //needed to be checked\
\

\f1\b Flow 
\f0\b0 \
npm start - index.html is served in the browser. index.html contains the root DOM node. Then control enters in index.js file. React DOM renders the App component on to the root DOM node. The App component contains HTML (App.js) which is ultimately displayed in the browser.\
\

